Nuclear Engineering and Design

Volume 249, August 2012, Pages 204-211

Argon entrainment into liquid sodium in fast breeder reactor

Author links open overlay panel, , , , ,
https://doi.org/10.1016/j.nucengdes.2011.07.046Get rights and content

Abstract

Gas entrainment in pool type sodium cooled fast breeder reactors has been a subject of great interest for a quite long time now. The issue of entrainment of argon cover gas in LMFBR's is being addressed by fundamental studies. Present work focuses on characterization of onset of shear type entrainment and liquid fall type entrainment based on mean velocity and turbulent kinetic energy at liquid surface. Study also includes characterization of onset of vortex type entrainment based on mean velocities (time averaged) in the outlet pipe. Experiments were carried out to characterize shear type entrainment in stirred tank with different impeller geometries with air–water and xylene–water systems. Onset of liquid fall type entrainment was studied with cylindrical tank with a nozzle whose input angle varied. Mean and r.m.s. velocity profiles near the liquid surface were measured with the help of ultrasonic velocity profiler (UVP). The results are compared with other literature. It is observed that the onset of entrainment can be characterized by the turbulent kinetic energy near the free liquid surface. Re-submergence angle was measured and r.m.s. velocities found to be in the same range as in case of shear type of entrainment. Cylindrical tank with tangential inlet and bottom outlet was used to study onset of vortex formation. Effect of different parameters like outlet diameter, tank diameter and liquid height in the tank on critical velocity was studied and correlation has been proposed.

Highlights

► In the present work, different types of entrainment mechanisms have been studied. ► Onset of entrainment could be characterized with turbulent intensities. ► For vortex type entrainment, a correlation has been proposed.

1. Introduction

Gas entrainment is a phenomenon in which the gas present on the surface of liquid gets entrapped into the bulk liquid in the form of bubbles. The literature shows three main types of entrainment (Madarame and Chiba, 1990) viz. shearing type, liquid fall type and vortex type. Vortex type entrainment is observed in many applications. Occurrence of vortices in tanks at pump suction is problematic due to cavitation in pump and durability of pump internals. Gas entrainment is a major problem in fast breeder reactors (FBR) since compact design of reactor results in higher surface velocities in upper plenum of reactor. These higher surface velocities cause shearing of liquid sodium surface results in argon gas getting entrained in liquid sodium pool. Entrained argon bubbles may pass through FBR internals. This entrained argon can cause operational problems such as pump cavitation, fluctuations in pump discharge, reduction in heat exchange efficiency, thermal stresses in the reactor structure and also induce reactivity problems in the reactor core. Shearing of liquid surface causes wave formation which can entrain gas in the form of bubbles into the liquid as shown in Fig. 1. Liquid fall type entrainment occurs when flow of liquid impinges on the free surface and forms local hump above liquid surface and again falls back. During this process bubble gets entrapped as shown in Fig. 2. Gas entrainment due to drain type vortex occurs due to high downward velocity component in bulk of liquid Fig. 3.

2. Previous work

Baum and Cook (1975) performed experiments with acrylic cylinder which had tangential input and bottom outlet located at centre. They performed experiments with different working fluids and proposed a correlation which shows effect of dimensionless numbers (Froude number, Weber number) on gas entrainment.(1)HD=700Fr0.5−4.4FrWeSverak and Hruby (1981) investigated the mechanism of surface aeration by vortex formation. They assumed that, the process of vortex formation can be characterized by the Froude number (Fr) and the Strouhal number (Sl) defined as:(2)Fr=Uav2gdWhereUav=q*(πdU2/4)(3)Sl=NDq*/(πdU2/4)Strouhal number is defined on the basis of flow rate q* at which the gas bubbles start to get entrapped into the liquid.

Ervine and Falvey (1987) studied air entrainment in open channel and observed that air entrainment occurs when the turbulence level is large enough to overcome both surface tension and gravity effects. They observed that the air is entrapped by turbulent velocity fluctuations at the free surface. They reported that air entrainment occurs when the turbulent velocities normal to the free surface become greater than 0.1–0.3 m/s.

Madarame and Chiba (1990) performed experiments to identify conditions leading to gas entrainment at the re-submerging point of a water jet into the liquid pool. Based on the submergence of the inlet nozzle (H) and the width of the plenum (W), they observed that free surface swell and waterfall induced entrainment occurred whenever the re-submerging velocity (V) is high (Fig. 2). Their results indicated that when the re-submerging velocity is such that (Fr · We)1/4 > 2, entrainment takes place.

Hagiwara et al. (1991) performed similar experiments and concluded that the liquid fall entrainment is governed not only by the re-submerging velocity but also by the re-submerging angle. They found that for re-submerging velocity <0.8 m/s, the critical re-submerging angle is 12°. If the angle exceeds 12°, entrainment takes place. If the velocity exceeds 0.8 m/s, the critical angle for entrainment was found to decrease.

Govindaraj et al. (1993) performed experiments in cylindrical tank which has tangential entry and bottom outlet. They have performed experiments with perforated plate at inlet in order to reduce turbulence at free surface. They proposed a correlation for onset of entrainment,(4)HD=1.4Fr0.5hd0.0425Eguchi and Tanaka, 1992, Eguchi and Tanaka, 1994, performed experiments to study gas entrainment at the free surface of water. Three geometrically similar models of having lengths 0.3 m, 1 m and 3 m were constructed for the experiment. The purpose of their study was to determine the effect of scaling on the onset of gas entrainment. The effect of liquid viscosity was also investigated. It was observed that an increase in the viscosity tends to suppress the gas entrainment. They have measured the critical velocity at the inlet for the onset of entrainment. They have concluded that the critical Froude number (calculated based on the critical velocity), above which gas entrainment occurs, is a strong function of the model scale. The critical Froude number was found to reduce with an increase in the scale of the equipment.

Bhattacharya et al. (2007) studied air entrainment in baffled stirred tanks. They performed experiments to determine the effect of impeller submergence, impeller diameter and physical properties of fluid on the onset of gas entrainment for up-pumping (PBTU) and down-pumping pitched blade turbine (PBTD). They have measured mean (time averaged) and root mean square of the fluctuating velocities (r.m.s.) in the axial and radial directions 1.5 cm below liquid surface using laser Doppler velocimetry (LDV). They have presented a model to characterize the onset of gas entrainment. They have shown that the r.m.s. velocity and the mean velocity need to be in certain proportion for onset of gas entrainment.

Kimura et al. (2008) studied gas entrainment phenomenon experimentally using dipped plate just below the free surface of liquid to keep free surface calm thereby avoiding liquid fall type entrainment and shearing type entrainment. The vortex type of entrainment was still dominant in the region of gaps between dipped plate and reactor internals. They have concluded that vortex type entrainment results into highest quantity of gas entrapment.

It is clear from the previous work, that a fundamental study of the process of gas entrainment is needed. The onset of gas entrainment needs to be related to the hydrodynamic behavior near the liquid surface. There is lack of data at the onset of vortex formation. The effect of vessel diameter, outlet diameter; inlet angle on onset of vortex formation has not been studied in earlier studies. Important parameters governing the process of entrainment need to be identified. These are the objectives of the present work.

3. Experimental work

Gas entrainment due to shear has been studied with the help of different impeller geometries. Experiments for air–water have been carried out in 0.5 m diameter cylindrical tank. Experiments on xylene–water system have been carried out in a 0.19 m diameter acrylic tank. Both the tanks were equipped with four baffles with a width equal to 1/10th of the tank diameter. The experimental setup is shown in Fig. 4A. Three different impellers have been investigated for air–water system disc turbine (DT), pitched blade turbine downflow/upflow. The photographs are shown in Fig. 4B and C. The D/T ratio is varied from 0.30 to 0.65. Three different values of impeller submergence have been studied S = H/3, S = H/2, S = 2H/3. Experiments on xylene entrainment in water were conducted with disc turbine (DT), pitched blade turbine downflow (PBTD) impellers. Both impellers had D/T ratio equal to 0.52 and two values impeller submergence have been investigated S = 2H/3, S = 4H/5. For a particular geometry, impeller speed was increased till a critical value at which the gas entrainment phenomenon was observed. This speed is called the Critical speed for surface aeration and is denoted by NCSA. For xylene–water system, instantaneous velocities (axial and radial) have been measured 4 mm below the water surface at several radial locations. All the UVP measurements have been made midway between the two baffles.

Gas entrainment due to liquid fall has been studied with air–water system. Fig. 5A shows the experimental set up. It consists of cylindrical vessel of 0.5 m diameter with side inlet and bottom outlet, containing inside vertical cylindrical structure. Swell at the gas liquid interface was created by introducing flow with different inlet nozzle angles 0°, 30°, 45°, 60° and 90° (angle with horizontal). For a particular liquid height in the vessel, the inlet flow rate was varied till onset is achieved. This flow rate was noted for different liquid heights and different nozzle angles. Mean and r.m.s. velocities were measured in the region of entrainment in the axial and radial directions. Photographs were taken at free liquid surface at onset conditions. A representative photograph has been given as Fig. 5B. From such photographs swell height and re-submergence angle were calculated.

Experimental set-up for vortex type entrainment consists of cylindrical vessel of size 0.5 m diameter with side inlet and bottom outlet, vertical cylinder is placed inside of size 0.14 m diameter with windows at particular height as shown in Fig. 6. Experiments were conducted with test section as inside cylinder and vortex is formed by adjusting inlet and outlet flow rates. Inlet was given through window and outlet (0.051 m) is provided at bottom as shown in Fig. 6. Water level was maintained at particular height. Then both the outlets were adjusted simultaneously in order to form vortex at free surface and outlet velocity was measured. This velocity was defined as critical velocity, the velocity at which vortex just start to form at the free surface, i.e., onset of condition. The effect of outlet diameter on critical velocity was studied using orifices of size 0.0254 m, 0.0127 m placed at outlet. Effect of vessel diameter on critical velocities studied in a 0.4 m diameter cylinder. Inlet to test section is given tangentially with two outlets at bottom, one located at centre of size 0.051 m and other near the wall of size 0.0381 m diameter. Inlet and outlet flow rates were adjusted such that onset condition is obtained and velocities were measured at different heights.

4. Results and discussion

4.1. Gas entrainment due to shear

Observed values of critical speed for surface aeration (NCSA) for air–water system for various impellers (DT, PBTD, PBTU) at different locations (S = H/3, H/2, 2H/3) and different D/T ratios (D/T = 0.65, 0.45, 0.3) are listed in Table 1. For each impeller, it is observed that an increase in submergence leads to an increase in NCSA. Also an increase in size of impeller resulted in a decrease of NCSA for each type of impeller. From the table it can also be seen that the values of NCSA differ over a very wide range. The lowest value of NCSA for largest impeller diameter and lowest submergence is about 40 rpm. The highest value of NCSA for lowest impeller diameter and highest submergence is about 400 rpm.

This represents an order of magnitude (10-fold) variation in the NCSA values. The mean shear velocities acting on the interface were calculated as(5)VShear=(Vr2+Vθ2)Fig. 7 shows the variation of mean shear velocity in the radial direction for different impellers of D/T = 0.45 at S = 2H/3. It was observed that the entrainment occurs in the regions of high shear velocity. Thus, for each impeller, the highest value of mean shear velocity was noted, this is denoted as ‘Vpeak’ these are listed in Table 2. For PBTU, peak shear velocity at the onset of entrainment is found to be higher as compared to DT and NCSA differ by a factor of two. For PBTU, peak shear velocity at the onset of entrainment is found to be higher as compared to DT and PBTD impellers. For both DT and PBTD, there is flow of liquid from the walls towards shaft near the liquid surface. Whereas, in the case of PBTU the liquid surface experiences a strong upward jet like flow. The values of Vpeak are tabulated in Table 2 for all the cases. From Table 2, it can be seen that the maximum variation in Vpeak for DT and PBTD impellers is found to be between 0.14 and 0.37 m/s (variation by a factor of 2.5). This indicates that the process of gas entrainment cannot be characterized in terms of the peak shear velocity. It was therefore thought desirable to compare the characteristics near the liquid surface and see if they correlate with the onset of entrainment. From the measured values of instantaneous velocities in all the three directions, the values of turbulent kinetic energy were calculated as,(6)k=12(Vz,rms2+Vr,rms2+Vθ,rms2)The values of turbulent kinetic energy for DT, PBTD, PBTU at S = H/2 (D/T = 0.45) are plotted in Fig. 8. It can be seen from figure that the values of maximum turbulent kinetic energy (kmax) for all the three impeller are similar and vary over a narrow range. The values of kmax for all the geometries and operating conditions are listed in Table 3. It can be seen that the values of kmax for D/T = 0.45 and 0.6 vary from 0.075 to 0.132 m2/s2. This represents a variation by a factor of 1.8. For D/T = 0.45 and 0.6, the variation in NCSA is found to be between 40 and 175 rpm (factor of 4.4). Thus, it can be concluded that the values of turbulent kinetic energy at the onset of gas entrainment are similar over a wide range of geometry and operating conditions. The variation of r.m.s. velocities in axial, radial and tangential directions with the radial location for DT (D/T = 0.45 at S = H/3) is shown in Fig. 9. It can be seen from this figure that the r.m.s. velocity in the axial direction is much larger than the two directions. Further, the values of r.m.s. velocities in the tangential and radial directions are similar in magnitude. Similar trend was observed for different impellers of D/T = 0.65, 0.30 at different submergences S = H/3, H/2, 2H/3. This implies that the turbulence is highly non-isotropic near the liquid surface and that the r.m.s. velocity in the axial direction contributes predominantly to the turbulent kinetic energy.

4.1.1. Xylene–water system and comparison with air–water system

In order to check the applicability of the results obtained so far, experiments have been carried for xylene–water system. The interfacial tension for air–water and xylene–water systems differs almost by a factor of two. Further the density and the viscosity of the entrained phase (air or xylene) differ by a large factor. For the entrainment of xylene the r.m.s. velocities in the axial and radial directions were measured. The process of surface entrainment would be characterized by the ratio of kinetic energy and surface tension. It was thought desirable to plot the ratio of turbulent kinetic energy divided by surface tension (σ) for air–water surface tension (σ) for air–water and xylene–water system. This plot is shown in Fig. 10. From the figure, it can be seen that the peak value of this ratio is in the range 0.75–1.0 for both air–water as well as xylene–water system. Since the phenomena of gas entrainment is a surface phenomena involving balance of the inertial forces and surface tension forces, it could be characterized by a dimensionless number involving these two processes (such as the Weber number, Froude). At the reactor conditions, liquid sodium has properties very similar to that of water. However, the interfacial tension between sodium and argon is likely to be different from air and water. However, more detailed experiments would be needed to properly calculate the critical value of such dimensionless numbers.

4.2. Liquid fall type entrainment

Nozzle velocities causing the onset of entrainment for different liquid heights and different inlet nozzle angles are listed in Table 4. It can be observed that for a given nozzle angle, an increase in liquid height leads to an increase the inlet velocity required for the onset of entrainment. The surface disturbance, swell and liquid fall velocities reduce with an increase in the liquid height. It can also be seen that for a given liquid height in the test section, an increase in inlet nozzle angle (0–90° with horizontal) resulted in a decrease in the inlet velocity required to cause the onset of entrainment. This is because; an increase in the nozzle angle makes the jet more oriented towards the surface, the liquid swell and the liquid fall is stronger. Comparing all the data, it can also be seen that the nozzle angle and the liquid height dramatically affect the velocity required for onset of entrainment.

4.2.1. Radial and axial mean velocities

Fig. 11 shows the profile of radial mean velocity in the radial direction along the measurement angle 60° for different nozzle angles for 0.35 m liquid heights. The region of entrainment was observed to be around r/R of −0.5. It can be observed that an increase in the inlet nozzle angle leads to an increase in the mean velocity in the radial direction in the region of entrainment. From Fig. 11 the mean radial velocities were found to be 0.15 m/s, 0.24 m/s and 0.27 m/s for 30°, 45° and 60° nozzles, respectively. At the conditions of onset of entrainment, photographs of liquid swell were taken. From these photographs, the swell height and liquid re-submergence angle were measured.

The values of swell height and the re-submergence angle for liquid height of 0.35 m are shown in Table 5 from this table it can be seen that swell height increases with an increase in the nozzle angle for a given liquid height. The re-submergence angle is strongly affected that at the onset of entrainment, higher axial and radial velocities are necessary for lower values of the re-submergence angle. Hagiwara et al. (1991) reported similar observations. When the nozzle angle is increased with respect to the horizontal, the jet will have higher axial component of velocity, when such flow causes a swell, the resulting liquid swell height would be higher and the liquid fall would have correspondingly higher radial velocity. Madarame and Chiba (1990) studied gas entrainment proposed a correlation for air–water system; the critical velocity obtained from above correlation is around 0.2 m/s. The values of the re-submergence velocity observed in this work are slightly lower than this.

4.2.2. Axial r.m.s. velocities

The r.m.s. velocities in the radial direction were also measured shows the r.m.s. velocity in the axial direction for different nozzle angles at different liquid levels. It can be seen that the r.m.s. velocities in the axial direction for different nozzle angles are all in the range 0.1 m/s listed in Table 6. It can be seen that the values of r.m.s. velocities are almost the same irrespective of the changes in the liquid height, the re-submergence angle, the inlet velocity and the nozzle angle. It can be thus seen that, in spite of the wide variation in the nozzle velocities, the r.m.s. velocities at the onset of entrainment are very similar for different operating conditions. Thus the r.m.s. velocities in the axial direction can be taken as a good indicator of the phenomenon of onset of entrainment.

4.3. Gas entrainment due to vortex formation

4.3.1. Effect of orifice plate

By adjusting outlet velocity for different liquid levels at which vortex formation just starts is noted. This velocity is normalized as Froude number (V2/gd) and height is normalized with vessel diameter. Fig. 12 shows that increase in size of orifice at outlet pipe resulted in decrease in Froude number. This data shows good comparison with Govindaraj et al. (1993) data, Baum and Cook (1975) data. When Fr values at particular H/D value are compared, 0.0254 m orifice required approximately 25 times higher value and 0.0127 m orifice required approximately 190 times higher values than that for 0.051 m outlet. This may be because reduction in outlet cross sectional are resulted increase in velocity and critical Froude number. For 0.4 m tank it can be observed that an increase in outlet size resulted in decrease in Froude number (Fig. 13) same as in case of 0.14 m tank. The photographs taken during experiments and size of the vortex measured 2 cm below the free surface for 0.051 m and 0.0254 m using distance tool in Adobe PDF.

4.3.2. Effect of H/D

Effect of H/D on critical Froude number has been investigated. Tank of 0.14 m has been used as a test section (Fig. 12). It is observed that increase in H/D causes increase in critical Froude number. Similar nature is observed for both 0.0254 m and 0.0127 m orifice. Vortex formation at the free surface is governed by a downward velocity component, which depends upon bottom outlet velocities and hence critical Froude number. It can be observed that there is a distinct change in the behavior at about H/D of 1.5. Above H/D of 1.5, the vortex is stable and has a size of 6.5 cm whereas below H/D of 1.5, vortex is quite unstable and varies in size. This could possibly be due to the proximity of outlet nozzle at lower H/D. However, more detailed measurements would be necessary to further characterize this phenomena.

4.3.3. Effect of normalizing parameter

The parameter used for normalizing height also has effect on spread of critical Froude number. When Froude number and normalized height for all geometries and all outlet orifices plotted together (Fig. 14) taking normalizing parameter as diameter of tank shows wide spread of Froude number values, hence difficult to predict any correlation. But when outlet orifice diameter used as normalizing parameter for height in tank data points shows very small variation. A proposed correlation is,(7)Hd=16V2gd0.2The above correlation is valid for the following ranges: 0.1 m < H < 0.5 m, 0.012 m < d < 0.075 m, and the corresponding velocity 0.1 m/s < V < 3 m/s. The reproducibility of velocity was found to be around 15%.

5. Conclusions

Present work was carried out to characterize onset of shearing type entrainment based on mean velocity and turbulent kinetic energy at the liquid surface. The turbulent kinetic energy at the liquid surface can be used as a characteristic measure of the process of entrainment. The values of r.m.s. velocities in the axial direction are found to be much higher as compared to the r.m.s. velocities in the other two directions. In case of liquid fall type entrainment it was observed that an increase in the inlet nozzle angle (with horizontal) leads to an increase in the axial velocity required for the onset of entrainment. The r.m.s. velocity in the axial direction in the region of entrainment is found to have the similar value over a wide range of liquid heights, inlet nozzle angles, inlet velocity and re-submergence angle. The process of entrainment of gas–liquid and liquid–liquid system can be characterized by the ratio of turbulent kinetic energy to surface tension. From results of drain type vortex we can conclude that, an increase in size of outlet orifice from 0.051 m to 0.0254 m and 0.0127 m caused increase in critical Froude number. An increase in normalized liquid level (H/D) inside test section resulted into increase in critical velocity. A correlation has been proposed to characterize vortex formation in tanks.

  • Hydrodynamics around a shroud tube assembly of a fast breeder reactor

    2017, Nuclear Engineering and Design
    Citation Excerpt :

    As a result, control rod deflects away from its center position in the shroud tube developing eccentricity causing uneven flow and temperature distribution in the coolant pool. Gas entrainment in the coolant pool occurs due to several factors i.e. formation of vortex dimple at free surface, temperature dependent dissolution of cover gas in sodium, sloshing and breaking of surface waves causing shearing of free surface and entrapment of bubbles (Winterton, 1972; Satpathy et al., 2013; Patwardhan et al., 2012; Madarame and Chiba, 1990; Eguchi et al., 1994). Several studies have been carried out on CP design and fluid flow characterization around the CP assembly.

    Control plug assembly of a liquid sodium cooled fast breeder reactor is partially submerged inside the liquid sodium coolant pool, free surface of which is blanketed with cover gas, mainly Argon to provide a non-reactive environment. It receives high velocity coolant flow from the fuel subassembly which travels through annular gap inside Control Safety Rod Driving Mechanism (CSRDM) assembly leading to swelling of free surface and gas entrainment inside the coolant pool. Entrained gas bubbles travel through different submerged components of the reactor and induces numerous complications including reactor power fluctuation, cavitation in inlet pumps and heat transfer inhibition in heat exchangers. Study of hydrodynamics around the shroud tube is crucial to examine cover gas entrainment inside the pool. The present study reports an experimental study on a 1:9 scale down model of CSRDM shroud tube assembly based on Froude number similarity. Eccentricity of the control rod inside the shroud tube is also an important parameter as temperature gradient along the CSRDM assembly leads to longitudinal thermal stress causing displacement of control rod from its center position in the shroud tube. Flow behavior around shroud tube, hump formation at the axial exit of shroud tube, air entrainment inside coolant pool have been reported for various parameters viz. inlet flow rate (), free surface height () and eccentricity of central rod (). Dye visualization, Schlieren visualization, Bulk visualization have been carried out and digital image processing techniques have been adopted for quantification of hump parameters and entrained air fraction inside the coolant pool.
